</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">N<sup>0</sup> 2</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Irishman who was formerly of the Artillery<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We do not find so many musquitoes here as we did to the Eastwards but the common house fly supply their places plentifully<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Monday 14<sup>th</sup> </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This morn we provided ourselves with some necessary articles for the Trade of the Missisourie Fifty pounds Pimigan and as many pounds of dried meat formed all our provisions for the Journey.  Each of us had about Fifty pounds Baggage with arms and our own weight became a heavy burden for a Horse.  Supplied with a compass and <span class="AddHand-author">a</span> spy glass<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>t 9 AM we took our departure directing our course Westerly towards <span style="text-decoration:underline;">La Tête d&#8217;orignal</span> where we arrived at noon and stopped to refresh.  This Country is destitute of wood<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  From the top of the hills we had a delightful prospect and numberless herds of Roe bucks were continually in Sight<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In the afternoon fell upon River La Sourcie at Plumb River and we Encamped at Sun set on the north bank near Fort La Trimer<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Here we found fresh Encampments of horse Stealers.  We passed an unpleasant night watching our horses annoyed with flies.  And a heavy storm croaded us with our baggage under the shelter of a fifteen ell tent when laying in a manner upon each other<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We were almost suffocated with heat and Musquitoes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Friday 15<sup>th</sup> </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">When day light appeared the rain having ceased though wet to the skin we proceeded.  The Soil upon the banks of this River is sandy</p>
